.`\n\n  Line 28: - Expected signals: Hook fires and logs a warning on mismatch (default); throws and blocks the dispatch when `MK_DEEP_LOOP_GUARD_REJECT=1` is set; stays silent on matching modes, non-deep `subagent_type` values, and when the registry is unreadable.\n\n  Line 39: - Feature catalog entry exists at `feature_catalog/03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md`.\n\n  Line 43: 1. Run the automated regression test: `node .opencode/plugins/__tests__/mk-deep-loop-guard.test.cjs` and require EXIT 0.\n\n  Line 44: 2. Live warn-mode check: dispatch a Task call with `subagent_type=ai-council` and a prompt containing `mode=research` via `opencode run --agent general \"...\"`; confirm `[mk-deep-loop-guard] WARN: ... mode mismatch ...` appears and the dispatch still completes.\n\n  Line 45: 3. Live reject-mode check: repeat step 2 with `MK_DEEP_LOOP_GUARD_REJECT=1` set; confirm the `task` tool call's status becomes `\"error\"` and the dispatch is blocked.\n\n  Line 57: - `MK_DEEP_LOOP_GUARD_REJECT=1` no longer blocks the dispatch (OpenCode host behavior change, or a regression in the throw path).\n\n  Line 69: | `.opencode/plugins/mk-deep-loop-guard.js` | OpenCode plugin entrypoint; registers and implements the `tool.execute.before` hook. |\n\n  Line 75: | `.opencode/plugins/__tests__/mk-deep-loop-guard.test.cjs` | Hermetic regression coverage for export shape, warn/reject toggle, fail-open, and non-deep passthrough. |\n\n  Line 83: - Feature catalog entry: `feature_catalog/03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md`\n\n  Line 84: - Scenario file path: `manual_testing_playbook/03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/feature_catalog/03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"mk-deep-loop-guard\"\n\n  Line 5:   - \"mk-deep-loop-guard\"\n\n  Line 12: # mk-deep-loop-guard (tool.execute.before plugin)\n\n  Line 34: Default behavior is mutate-and-warn: on a mismatch, it logs `[mk-deep-loop-guard] WARN: ...` and lets the dispatch proceed. Setting `MK_DEEP_LOOP_GUARD_REJECT=1` switches to fail-closed: the hook throws, which blocks the dispatch (confirmed via live testing against the installed OpenCode host — throwing from `tool.execute.before` genuinely prevents the underlying tool call from executing, not merely logging a warning).\n\n  Line 52: | `.opencode/plugins/mk-deep-loop-guard.js` | Script | OpenCode plugin entrypoint; registers the `tool.execute.before` hook. |\n\n  Line 58: | `.opencode/plugins/__tests__/mk-deep-loop-guard.test.cjs` | Automated test | Hermetic regression coverage for export shape, warn/reject toggle, fail-open, and non-deep passthrough, run against a fixture registry (no live OpenCode session required). |\n\n  Line 60: Live-verified against a real `opencode` session during development (hook registration, warn-mode logging, reject-mode blocking, fail-open on a missing registry, and pass-through for non-deep `subagent_type` values) — see `.opencode/specs/deep-loops/031-deep-loop-issues-with-gpt-opencode/011-deep-route-guard-plugin/implementation-summary.md` for the full evidence trail.\n\n  Line 69: - Feature file path: `03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md`\n\n  Line 70: - Primary sources: `.opencode/plugins/mk-deep-loop-guard.js`, `.opencode/plugins/__tests__/mk-deep-loop-guard.test.cjs`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:\n  Line 25: | [03--validation](03--validation/) | 3 features | `lib/deep-loop/post-dispatch-validate.ts`, `.opencode/plugins/mk-deep-loop-guard.js` |\n\n  Line 164: ### mk-deep-loop-guard\n\n  Line 172: A `tool.execute.before` hook resolves the target `subagent_type` against `mode-registry.json` and compares it to any `mode=X` value declared in the dispatch prompt. Default is mutate-and-warn; `MK_DEEP_LOOP_GUARD_REJECT=1` switches to fail-closed (throws, blocking the dispatch — confirmed live against the installed OpenCode host). Fails open on its own internal errors.\n\n  Line 176: See [`03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md`](03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md) for full implementation and validation file listings.\n","metadata":{"matches":33,"truncated":false},"title":"deep-route-guard|DEEP_ROUTE_GUARD|mk-deep-loop-guard|MK_DEEP_LOOP_GUARD","time":{"start":1782919103749,"end":1782919103930}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c0a1c33a516776a016a452fbf2e5081989320b8fb907fc9d4"}},"id":"prt_f1e4284b3001eenR2DwltKvAzY","sessionID":"ses_0e1c04adcffe04QJWsDQQqIgY4","messageID":"msg_f1e4214830010Zd3w5awbnkB71"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782919103936,"sessionID":"ses_0e1c04adcffe04QJWsDQQqIgY4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_xjhW8BNb5NEHbq4AIZU92oP6","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"orchestrate|@deep-context|@deep-review|Deep Route|mode-registry|@deep\\b","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 222: Detection-layer OpenCode plugin that flags/blocks a Task dispatch whose declared Deep Route mode disagrees with `mode-registry.json`'s entry for the actual `subagent_type` being dispatched.\n\n  Line 225: Prompt: `Verify mk-deep-loop-guard still detects a Deep Route mode mismatch and respects MK_DEEP_LOOP_GUARD_REJECT.`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/SKILL.md:\n  Line 250:        ├─ native seats → parallel batch of @deep-context Task subagents\n\n  Line 279: The native `@deep-context` seat is dispatched **by name** (`agent: deep-context` in the loop YAML), resolved by each host runtime from its OWN `agents/` directory. It therefore lives as one canonical source plus two runtime mirrors that must stay in sync:\n\n  Line 413: | Agent | `@deep-context` (LEAF, read-only analyzer seat) |\n\n  Line 418: | Default pool | 2 native `@deep-context` seats (native-only), over the shared scope; add `--executor` for CLI/heterogeneous |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/SKILL.md:\n  Line 223: The ask-first rule above governs **in-session** decisions: once an AI is running, it must not autonomously create a worktree. That is distinct from `.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh`, a **launch wrapper** the operator opts into at the shell (e.g. `alias claude='bash /abs/.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh claude'`). The wrapper runs *before* the AI starts and places each top-level session in its own worktree + branch + isolated MCP databases automatically; orchestrated children (`AI_SESSION_CHILD=1`, or already inside a linked worktree) exec in place. Because the wrapper acts pre-session at operator opt-in, it does not violate the in-session ask-first rule — the operator made the choice by aliasing the launch.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/lib/council/README.md:\n  Line 29: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-topic.cjs`\n\n  Line 30: - `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/scripts/orchestrate-session.cjs`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/SKILL.md:\n  Line 41: - A user requests an interactive command (use `/deep:review` or `/deep:research` instead — those orchestrate this runtime)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 45: - `@deep-context` agent definition exists at `.opencode/agents/deep-context.md`.\n\n  Line 236: Verify that `step_sweep_native_batch` dispatches all native `@deep-context` seats in a single parallel Task batch, each receiving the four-part lineage contract, and that the agent definition enforces the LEAF read-only boundary.\n\n  Line 239: Prompt: As a manual-testing orchestrator, validate the native Task batch dispatch contract for `deep-context` against the auto YAML, the `@deep-context` agent definition, and loop_protocol.md. Verify `step_sweep_native_batch` dispatches a parallel Task batch (not sequential), each seat receives gather-subject + scope/slice + known-context + output schema, and the agent is LEAF-only (no writes, no sub-agent dispatch). Return a concise verdict.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/SKILL.md:\n  Line 13: Note: `Task` is allowed for the command executor that manages the loop. The `@deep-research` agent itself is LEAF-only and does not dispatch sub-agents.\n\n  Line 276: Never simulate the loop with ad hoc shell dispatch, nested CLI loops, direct `@deep-research` Task dispatch, `/tmp` prompt files, or state outside the resolved local research packet.\n\n  Line 280: The YAML workflow owns executor selection. Native `@deep-research` is the default path; CLI executors are routed through the workflow, not through ad hoc shell loops.\n\n  Line 333: `/deep:research` owns the YAML workflow, which initializes state, dispatches one LEAF iteration at a time, evaluates convergence, synthesizes `research/research.md`, and saves continuity. The `@deep-research` agent executes only one research cycle per dispatch.\n\n  Line 355: Init creates config, strategy, and state logs. Each loop reads state, checks convergence, dispatches `@deep-research`, writes iteration markdown and JSONL deltas, refreshes reducer-owned state, and either continues or synthesizes and saves continuity.\n\n  Line 394: 1. **Dispatch sub-agents** -- @deep-research is LEAF-only (NDP compliance)\n\n  Line 402: 9. **Simulate loop dispatch** -- Do not write custom shell loops, nested CLI loops, `/tmp` prompt dispatchers, or direct Task loops for `@deep-research`. **Command-driven fan-out via `step_fanout_spawn` in the YAML is SUPPORTED** — use `--executor`/`--executors`/`--concurrency` flags on the command; ad-hoc shell fan-out and intra-lineage wave orchestration remain forbidden.\n\n  Line 476: - **Orchestrator**: @orchestrate dispatches @deep-research as LEAF agent\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/assets/solid_checklist.md:\n  Line 46: - A single function orchestrates unrelated workflows.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/manual_testing_playbook/03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md:\n  Line 15: Detection-layer OpenCode plugin (`tool.execute.before` hook) that flags/blocks a Task dispatch whose declared Deep Route mode disagrees with `mode-registry.json`'s entry for the actual `subagent_type` being dispatched.\n\n  Line 19: If this plugin silently stops firing (hook deregistered, registry path resolution breaks, or the warn/reject toggle inverts), a real Deep Route mismatch could go undetected in production dispatch, or a false positive could start blocking unrelated correctly-routed work.\n\n  Line 27: - Real user request: `Verify mk-deep-loop-guard still detects a Deep Route mode mismatch and respects MK_DEEP_LOOP_GUARD_REJECT.`\n\n  Line 46: 4. Live fail-open check: temporarily move `mode-registry.json` aside, repeat step 3; confirm the dispatch completes normally (not blocked) despite reject mode being on.\n\n  Line 58: - A missing/corrupt `mode-registry.json` starts blocking unrelated dispatches instead of failing open.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/SKILL.md:\n  Line 31: 2. Gate validation: score + pass/fail recommendation for orchestrated workflows.\n\n  Line 80: - `references/review_core.md` for shared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 45: - `@deep-research` agent definition exists at `.opencode/agents/deep-research.md` plus runtime variants.\n\n  Line 210: Prompt summary: As a manual-testing orchestrator, validate the read-state-first iteration contract for deep-research against the current deep-research docs, command entrypoint, YAML workflow, and runtime anchors. Verify the loop dispatch and the @deep-research agent both require reading JSONL and strategy state before any research actions. Return a concise operator verdict.\n\n  Line 731: Validate that the command-dispatched `@deep-research` body writes a cited iteration file and exactly one schema-rich JSONL iteration record.\n\n  Line 739: Validate that command-dispatched `@deep-research` reads existing state and does not retry a BLOCKED exhausted approach.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/SKILL.retired.md:\n  Line 107:     \"PATTERNS\":          {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"pattern\", \"workflow\", \"orchestrate\", \"session\", \"resume\", \"fork\"]},\n\n  Line 362: 10. **Never inject user-level voice/personalization content into AI-orchestrated Codex delegations.** Codex CLI reads user-level voice from `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` (the human's global settings, loaded automatically). When an AI delegates via `codex exec`, the calling AI's own voice rules govern the response — do NOT read `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` and paste into delegation prompts. Keep delegations focused on task/model/sandbox/effort/(spec-folder pre-approval). If the user asks how to make Codex sound more like Claude in *their own* sessions, point to `~/.codex/AGENTS.md` — not any repo asset.\n\n  Line 364: 12. **Design Standards Loading (surface-aware contract)** — When dispatching for design or UI work, instruct the dispatched session to: (1) load `sk-design` (the hub); (2) let the hub resolve a `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json` (interface / foundations / motion / audit / md-generator); (3) load the selected mode packet, set the design register, and run that mode's design verification; (4) if the work feeds Open Design, carry the `mcp-open-design` pairing — the transport never decides taste. Fallback: if the design mode cannot be determined confidently, ask for the surface and design intent. NEVER treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as the taste authority, or hardcode obsolete flat design skills in dispatch prompts.\n\n  Line 367: 15. **Set `AI_SESSION_CHILD=1` in the dispatched child's env** when sessions may be launched through the per-session worktree wrapper (`.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh`). A dispatched `codex exec` is an orchestrated sub-session, not a new top-level session, so it must SHARE the parent's worktree rather than allocate its own. The wrapper checks `AI_SESSION_CHILD` (plus a `git --git-common-dir` structural backstop) and exec's in place when set. Pattern: `AI_SESSION_CHILD=1 codex exec ... </dev/null`. Harmless when the wrapper is not in use. See `.opencode/bin/README.md` → \"Worktree session isolation\".\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/frontmatter_templates.md:\n  Line 269: - Primary verb (`orchestrate`, `validate`, `dispatch`, `audit`)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 82: - Deep-review references shown as `agent: @deep-review <single-iteration context>` only when a scenario inspects deep-review behavior; this root playbook does not run the deep-review loop.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/manual_testing_playbook/03--reasoning-effort/high-xhigh-override.md:\n  Line 19: SKILL.md §3 + `integration_patterns.md` §5 explicitly recommend `high` / `xhigh` for architecture, security and complex planning. If these levels silently degrade to `medium` behavior, every routing recommendation that depends on depth (`@review`, `@ai-council`, `@deep-research`) loses its quality edge.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_templates.md:\n  Line 185: Common slugs: `general`, `context`, `orchestrate`, `write`, `review`, `debug`, `deep-research`, `deep-review`, `ai-council`, `deep-improvement`.\n\n  Line 266: **Agent:** `general` or `orchestrate`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md:\n  Line 28: - **Full plugin / skill / MCP runtime** (use case 1) — calling AI is Claude Code / OpenCode / Copilot / raw shell AND the task needs the project's full Spec Kit Memory database, Code Graph semantic index, structural code graph, or every plugin/skill/MCP tool in a one-shot dispatch. Includes `@deep-research` / `@deep-review` agent loops with externalized state under `.opencode/specs/`.\n\n  Line 31: - **Agent dispatch** — task matches a specialized OpenCode agent. Primary agents (directly invokable via `--agent`): `general`, `plan` (built-in), `orchestrate`, `ai-council`. Subagents dispatched via the orchestrate primary: `context`, `review`, `write`, `debug`, `deep-research`, `deep-review`, `deep-improvement`, `prompt-improver`.\n\n  Line 123:     \"PATTERNS\":           {\"weight\": 3, \"keywords\": [\"pattern\", \"workflow\", \"orchestrate\", \"session continue\", \"resume session\"]},\n\n  Line 285: OpenCode defines `general`, `plan`, `orchestrate`, and `ai-council` as primary agents. **Caveat — never pass `--agent general`:** the current opencode treats `general` as a subagent and rejects it at the top level, and the default agent (used when no `--agent` is given) already covers that case. Pin `--agent plan|orchestrate|ai-council` only when the task needs that profile AND `opencode run --help` on the installed version confirms top-level acceptance; otherwise state the role in the prompt body.\n\n  Line 291: 1. **Generic subagents** (`context`, `review`, `write`, `debug`) — dispatched by a primary (`orchestrate`) using the Task tool. To exercise via the opencode CLI, route through `--agent orchestrate` and let it dispatch the relevant subagent.\n\n  Line 292: 2. **Command-owned loop executors** (`deep-research`, `deep-review`, `deep-improvement`, `prompt-improver`) — dispatched ONLY by their parent commands (`/deep:research`, `/deep:review`, `/deep:agent-improvement`, `/prompt`). Never dispatch these directly via `--agent <slug>` and never route them through `orchestrate`. The parent command owns iteration state, convergence detection, and continuity.\n\n  Line 294: Generic subagents (`context`, `review`, `write`, `debug`) route through `orchestrate`; loop executors (`deep-research`, `deep-review`, `deep-improvement`, `prompt-improver`) route only through their parent commands.\n\n  Line 304: Use the default invocation for external runtime handback, append `--share --port <N>` only for explicit detached sessions, select `--agent orchestrate` for generic subagent routing, and change `--dir` for cross-repo dispatch.\n\n  Line 331: 13. **Design Standards Loading (surface-aware contract)** — When dispatching for design or UI work, instruct the dispatched session to: (1) load `sk-design` (the hub); (2) let the hub resolve a `workflowMode` through `mode-registry.json` (interface / foundations / motion / audit / md-generator); (3) load the selected mode packet, set the design register, and run that mode's design verification; (4) if the work feeds Open Design, carry the `mcp-open-design` pairing — the transport never decides taste. Fallback: if the design mode cannot be determined confidently, ask for the surface and design intent. NEVER treat `mcp-figma` or `mcp-open-design` as the taste authority, or hardcode obsolete flat design skills in dispatch prompts.\n\n  Line 335: 17. **Set `AI_SESSION_CHILD=1` in the dispatched session's env** when sessions may be launched through the per-session worktree wrapper (`.opencode/bin/worktree-session.sh`). A dispatched `opencode run` is an orchestrated sub-session, not a new top-level session, so it must SHARE the parent's worktree rather than allocate its own. The wrapper checks `AI_SESSION_CHILD` (plus a `git --git-common-dir` structural backstop) and exec's in place when set. Pattern: `AI_SESSION_CHILD=1 opencode run ... </dev/null`. Harmless when the wrapper is not in use. See `.opencode/bin/README.md` → \"Worktree session isolation\".\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/agent_template.md:\n  Line 702: | `@deep-research` | `deep-research.md` | LEAF research subagent | Single research iteration, externalized state, convergence-driven command orchestration |\n\n  Line 703: | `@deep-review` | `deep-review.md` | LEAF review subagent | Single review iteration, BINDING emission, canonical REFUSE, scoped review packet writes |\n\n  Line 704: | `@deep-improvement` | `deep-improvement.md` | LEAF proposal mutator | Bounded candidate generation, evaluator-first promotion discipline |\n\n  Line 708: | `@orchestrate` | `orchestrate.md` | Primary orchestrator | Task decomposition, specialist routing, integration synthesis, delegation governance |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/manual_testing_playbook/02--by-model-parallel-sweep/native-task-batch.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"This scenario validates Native Task Batch for `SWEEP-002`. It focuses on the concurrent parallel Task dispatch of @deep-context LEAF seats and the read-only boundary enforced by the agent definition.\"\n\n  Line 15: This scenario validates Native Task Batch for `SWEEP-002`. It focuses on `step_sweep_native_batch` dispatching all native `@deep-context` seats as a single parallel Task batch (not sequential), each seat receiving the mandatory four-part lineage contract, and the `@deep-context` agent definition enforcing the LEAF read-only boundary.\n\n  Line 29: - Prompt: `As a manual-testing orchestrator, validate the native Task batch dispatch contract for deep-context against the auto YAML, the @deep-context agent definition, and loop_protocol.md. Verify step_sweep_native_batch dispatches a parallel Task batch (not sequential), each seat receives gather-subject + scope/slice + known-context + output schema, and the agent is LEAF-only (no writes, no sub-agent dispatch). Return a concise verdict.`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/assets/skill/parent_skill_hub_template.md:\n  Line 16: Template for the thin routing hub of a **parent skill**: one advisor-routable identity that dispatches by mode key through `mode-registry.json` to N verbatim, self-contained mode packets over a shared backend. The hub holds **no** per-mode logic.\n\n  Line 34: - `mode-registry.json` — the declarative single source of truth (use [parent_skill_registry_template.json](./parent_skill_registry_template.json)).\n\n  Line 45: description: \"[Unified skill: routes a request to one of N modes ([mode-a], [mode-b], …) over the shared [backend] backend. Holds no per-mode logic — dispatches by [modeKey] through mode-registry.json.]\"\n\n  Line 69: <!-- Keywords: [parent-skill-name], [mode-a], [mode-b], [modeKey], mode-registry, [backend], [domain keywords] -->\n\n  Line 73: [One sentence: N modes, one shared backend, one identity.] This hub holds NO per-mode logic — it routes by [modeKey] through `mode-registry.json`. Each mode keeps its own contract in its packet.\n\n  Line 94: Routing is **registry-driven**. `mode-registry.json` is the single source of truth; the hub, commands, and advisor all read it and none re-derive the mapping.\n\n  Line 103: read mode-registry.json\n\n  Line 119:   mode-registry.json     # the discriminator + advisorRouting (single source of truth)\n\n  Line 135: - **ALWAYS** resolve a mode through `mode-registry.json`; never hardcode a router mapping.\n\n  Line 143: - **NEVER** make the advisor read `mode-registry.json` at runtime — keep the projection maps in code and guard them with the drift-guard test.\n\n  Line 147: - A new mode is needed — extend `mode-registry.json` and open a packet; do not bolt logic onto the hub.\n\n  Line 157: - Registry: `mode-registry.json` (the routing contract).\n\n  Line 168: - [ ] `mode-registry.json` exists, every mode has an `advisorRouting` block.\n\n  Line 178: - [parent_skill_registry_template.json](./parent_skill_registry_template.json) - the companion `mode-registry.json` scaffold.\n\n  Line 180: - Canonical example: [`deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md`](../../../deep-loop-workflows/SKILL.md), [`mode-registry.json`](../../../deep-loop-workflows/mode-registry.json), [`graph-metadata.json`](../../../deep-loop-workflows/graph-metadata.json).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/README.md:\n  Line 55: The default pool runs 2 native `@deep-context` seats. Add CLI seats with `--executor` for a heterogeneous sweep.\n\n  Line 91: All seats sweep the same scope at once. Native `@deep-context` agents run as a parallel Task batch. Optional heterogeneous CLI seats (MiMo, gpt, deepseek, claude) dispatch through the deep-loop-runtime multi-seat pool. Both groups start together and barrier-join before the host merges anything. A seat that fails does not block the others, and the agreement count reflects only the seats that returned. Seats are read-only analyzers. The host writes all merged state, which keeps the loop Gate-3-safe.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/README.md:\n  Line 102: The fan-out scripts orchestrate multi-executor runs, including fixed-rate overrun accounting, an opt-in stall watchdog, and persisted-wait crash resume. `fanout-run.cjs` spawns headless CLI subprocesses into isolated `lineages/{label}/` directories. `fanout-pool.cjs` provides a concurrency-capped worker pool with a status ledger. `fanout-salvage.cjs` recovers missing iteration files from captured subprocess stdout. `fanout-merge.cjs` deduplicates findings across lineages into a consolidated registry. Each lineage gets its own session id so coverage-graph writes never collide. A shared CLI guard at `scripts/lib/cli-guards.cjs` normalizes argv validation across every entry point. The runtime also ships `sleep.ts`, `lifecycle-taxonomy.cjs`, `observability-events.cjs`, `createHermeticEnv()`, and record/replay cassette helpers for cancellable waits, lifecycle guards, telemetry envelopes, hermetic tests, and reproducible script regressions.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/feature_catalog/01--frontier-seeding/config-shape-and-default-pool.md:\n  Line 48: When no `--executor` / `--executors` flags or marker are present, the default heterogeneous pool is used: 2 native `@deep-context` Task seats + 1 MiMo-v2.5-pro seat (`cli-opencode`) + 1 gpt seat (`cli-opencode`) + 1 deepseek-v4-pro seat (`cli-opencode`). All seats sweep the same focus and agreement is the confidence signal. A single-seat pool is legal but yields no agreement signal; the command warns and continues.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 37: Coverage note (2026-04-26): Covers the canonical default invocation (`deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` + `--variant high` + `--agent general` + `--format json`), the three documented use cases (external dispatch, parallel detached, cross-AI handback per ADR-002), the multi-provider matrix (deepseek direct API default with full variant range, kimi-for-coding direct plan), the 8-agent routing surface (general / context / orchestrate / write / review / debug / deep-research / deep-review / ai-council), session continuity surfaces (`-c`, `-s <id>`, `--fork`, `--share` gate), the 16-template inventory plus CLEAR quality card, the parallel-detached exception path with `</dev/null` worker farms, cross-repo dispatch via `--dir` and cross-server dispatch via `--attach`. Self-invocation refusal (ADR-001) is enforced upstream by the skill's layered detection guard and is exercised in CO-008 (refusal path) and CO-031 (cross-repo nested guard) respectively. Destructive scenarios are limited to operator-confirmed `--share` flows (CHK-033). The playbook never publishes share URLs without explicit operator approval.\n\n  Line 362: This category covers 8 scenario summaries while the linked feature files remain the canonical execution contract. cli-opencode distinguishes 4 primary agents (directly invokable via --agent: general + plan as OpenCode built-ins; orchestrate + ai-council as repo-defined primaries) from N subagents (context, review, write, debug, deep-research, deep-review, deep-improvement, prompt-improver) which dispatch as Task subagents from a primary. CO-013..CO-017 + CO-032..CO-034 exercise both surfaces — direct primary invocation and primary-dispatches-subagent routing.\n\n  Line 465: Verify `--agent orchestrate` produces a sequenced multi-agent plan naming at least 3 distinct OpenCode agent slugs with explicit handoffs, AND that the JSON event stream contains zero nested `opencode run` tool.call events (per agent_delegation.md §6).\n\n  Line 469: Prompt summary: As an external-AI conductor facing a complex task that requires multiple OpenCode specializations in sequence, dispatch `opencode run --agent orchestrate --variant high --format json --dir <repo-root>` and ask for a decomposition naming at least 3 specialist agents (for example context, review, write, ai-council) and explicit handoffs. Verify the response names at least 3 distinct agent slugs in sequence with handoffs and that zero nested opencode-run tool.calls appear. Return a verdict naming the agents in planned order and confirming the no-nested-run constraint.\n\n  Line 471: Expected signals: Exit 0. >= 3 distinct agent slugs in sequence. Handoffs described. Zero nested `opencode run` tool.call events. Working tree clean. Dispatch line includes `--agent orchestrate`.\n\n  Line 475: > **Feature File:** [CO-034](04--agent-routing/orchestrate-agent-multi-agent.md)\n\n  Line 830: - CO-034: [Orchestrate agent multi-agent coordination](04--agent-routing/orchestrate-agent-multi-agent.md)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/README.md:\n  Line 133: | `orchestrate` | Multi-agent coordination | `--sandbox read-only` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/feature_catalog/03--agreement-merge/contradiction-surfacing.md:\n  Line 41: Contradictions are never silently resolved in the merge layer. When the host cannot reconcile from evidence (e.g. both seats cite different file:lines that both verify), the contradiction is surfaced as-is. The `@deep-context` agent is expected to surface contradictions in its finding set rather than picking one side (per its ESCALATE rule 4).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/quick_reference.md:\n  Line 31: - **Deep review only**: Core doctrine is loaded via the `@deep-review` agent contract\n\n  Line 39: | [review_core.md](./review_core.md) | Shared doctrine: severity, evidence, findings schema, baseline+surface precedence | `@review`, `@deep-review` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/references/review_core.md:\n  Line 18: Shared doctrine consumed by both `@review` and `@deep-review`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/feature_catalog/03--validation/mk-deep-loop-guard.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Detection-layer OpenCode plugin that flags/blocks a Task dispatch whose declared Deep Route mode disagrees with mode-registry.json's entry for the actual subagent_type being dispatched.\"\n\n  Line 8:   - \"Deep Route mode mismatch detection\"\n\n  Line 20: Detection-layer enforcement for Task-tool dispatches targeting deep-loop sub-agents. On every `task` dispatch, the plugin resolves the target `subagent_type` against `mode-registry.json` and compares it to any `mode=X` value declared in the dispatch prompt's Deep Route header; a mismatch is flagged.\n\n  Line 30: For each `task` dispatch, the plugin reads `mode-registry.json` fresh (no caching), maps `agent -> workflowMode`, and extracts a `mode=X` token from the outgoing prompt text via regex. If the target `subagent_type` isn't a registry entry, or no `mode=X` token is present, or the mode matches, the plugin is a no-op.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/z_archive/cli-codex-retired/references/agent_delegation.md:\n  Line 29: Documents the active Codex agents in `.codex/agents/` and how any AI assistant orchestrates them. The calling AI acts as the **conductor** (planner, validator, integrator) while Codex CLI executes targeted tasks through its agent system.\n\n  Line 35: - Web research via `--search` flag (`@deep-research`)\n\n  Line 37: - Multi-agent Codex-side workflows (`@orchestrate`)\n\n  Line 199: ### @orchestrate — Task Commander\n\n  Line 212: **Note:** Avoid double-orchestration. If the calling AI is already decomposing tasks, delegate directly to leaf agents instead of routing through @orchestrate.\n\n  Line 215: codex exec -p orchestrate \\\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"orchestrate|@deep-context|@deep-review|Deep Route|mode-registry|@deep\\b","time":{"start":1782919103832,"end":1782919103935}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c0a1c33a516776a016a452fbf2e70819894bc36401d234480"}},"id":"prt_f1e42855100133Xl1X7VvJGKIt","sessionID":"ses_0e1c04adcffe04QJWsDQQqIgY4","messageID":"msg_f1e4214830010Zd3w5awbnkB71"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782919104013,"sessionID":"ses_0e1c04adcffe04QJWsDQQqIgY4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_hRBx4dVm6hfEANeq4UckKPUg","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"FIX-5|host hard identity|semantic wrong-mode|route-proof mismatch|latency gap|GPT-vs-Claude|benchmark","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 100 matches (more matches available)\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/assets/pr_template.md:\n  Line 238: - **Performance**: No degradation (benchmarked)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-git/references/finish_workflows.md:\n  Line 633:   e4f5g6h Add performance benchmarks\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/ARCHITECTURE.md:\n  Line 87: │   ├── bench/              # Scorer benchmarks\n\n  Line 153: **Test surfaces.** Default `npm test` runs unit and integration suites under `mcp_server/tests/`. Scorer benchmarks run through `npm run bench`. Operator playbook scenarios live in `manual_testing_playbook/`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/changelog/v0.9.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release graduates the reciprocal-rank-fusion spine out of the dark and closes the self-recommendation hole the graduation exposed. The dark-flag-graduation benchmark phase 007 measured the RRF spine and the conflict-rerank seam on a widened 42-prompt set, and the verdict was GRADUATE the RRF core paired with the conflict-rerank seam and CUT the separate self-recommendation guard. The follow-up work then documented and locked the implicit penalty that did the guard's job, and a later opus deep review found the penalty matched only the exact id by string so the `skill-advisor` alias still self-recommended to the top. The penalty value is unchanged at -0.25 and the full scorer suite stayed green at 119 of 119.\n\n  Line 24: - **Default-off was byte-identical** across the 42 prompts, and no production default was flipped by the benchmark itself.\n\n  Line 35: No migration required. The RRF core and conflict-rerank seam graduate as the new defaults from the phase 007 benchmark, and default-off behavior was byte-identical across the 42-prompt set so no flag flip changes existing routing. The self-recommendation penalty value is unchanged at -0.25, so adopters see the same demotion magnitude for both the canonical id and the alias. Adopt via fresh session so the daemon respawns with the graduated defaults. Verify with an `advisor_recommend` for an audit or explainer phrase (expect neither `system-skill-advisor` nor the `skill-advisor` alias at top-1) and re-run the scorer suite (expect 119 of 119).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/references/scoring/validation_baselines.md:\n  Line 54: | Watcher idle CPU | 0.031% | `mcp_server/lib/daemon/watcher.ts` benchmark |\n\n  Line 155: - `mcp_server/bench/`, latency benchmark harnesses\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt-models/SKILL.md:\n  Line 232: 3. **Never present carried-forward evidence as fresh.** When a profile's frameworks are inherited (e.g. MiniMax-M3's TIDD-EC contract from benchmark 003, originally run on M2.7), label it carried and name the source benchmark — do not imply a fresh M3 run.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_templates.md:\n  Line 490: **When**: dispatching to the MiniMax Token Plan default `minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` (pay-per-token alternative `minimax/MiniMax-M3` via the Direct API). The 120/003 benchmark (real MiniMax M2.7 runs) found MiniMax diverges from the cross-model defaults: **TIDD-EC** framework + **dense** pre-planning wins (RCAF + medium is the fallback) — carry this contract forward to M3 until re-benchmarked. `--variant` is omitted by default (unverified). **Omit `--agent`** (rejected on opencode 1.15.13).\n\n  Line 531: **Why**: TIDD-EC's explicit Do's/Don'ts curb MiniMax's scope/format drift more than RCAF's role anchor (0.767 vs 0.742), and MiniMax uses dense plan structure rather than being slowed by it (0.775 dense vs 0.767 medium) — the opposite of SWE-1.6. Evidence: `.opencode/skills/sk-prompt-models/benchmarks/003-minimax-prompt-framework/eval-loop/synthesis.md`.\n\n  Line 537: **When**: dispatching to MiMo-V2.5-Pro via the Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — primary slug `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` (provider `xiaomi-token-plan-ams`, quota pool `xiaomi-token-plan`) — or via the Xiaomi Direct API — slugs `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` and the low-latency `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` (provider `xiaomi`, pay-per-token; pick UltraSpeed for latency-sensitive checks/smokes — same COSTAR contract). The 126/004 benchmark (10/10 real `mimo-v2.5-pro` runs) found **COSTAR wins** (RACE is a statistical-tie fallback); use **lean-to-medium** pre-planning. MiMo is frontier-correct already, so frame for format + brevity, **not** guardrails — TIDD-EC/dense ranked LAST, and CIDI is unreliable (it intermittently writes to a file instead of returning inline code). **Always pass `--variant high`** — opencode maps low/medium/high to MiMo's reasoning effort (confirmed accepted on opencode 1.15.13); high is the standing default. **Omit `--agent`** (on opencode 1.15.13 `--agent general` warns and falls back to the default agent). Confirm live model ids with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Token Plan) or `opencode models xiaomi` (Direct API).\n\n  Line 565: **Why**: MiMo-V2.5-Pro (1M-token context, strongly agentic — 1000+ tool calls, token-efficient; SWE-bench Pro 57.2) is an explicitly-selectable model on the Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) and the Xiaomi Direct API; the default skill model stays `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro`. The COSTAR/RACE-lean contract is the empirical 004 finding (10/10 real dispatches; the discriminator was format adherence + token efficiency, not correctness — MiMo solved every fixture under every framework). Evidence: `.opencode/skills/sk-prompt-models/benchmarks/004-mimo-prompt-framework/eval/synthesis.md`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md:\n  Line 50: | GLM-5.2 (Z.AI GLM Coding Plan) | COSTAR + lean (empirical, benchmark 008) | [`glm-5.2.md`](../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md) |\n\n  Line 51: | deepseek-v4-pro / kimi-k2.6 / qwen3.6 | default RCAF (no model-specific benchmark; shared default-unverified note) | [`deepseek-v4-pro.md`](../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/deepseek-v4-pro.md) · [`kimi-k2.6.md`](../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/kimi-k2.6.md) · [`qwen3.6.md`](../../sk-prompt-models/references/models/qwen3.6.md) |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/04--scorer-fusion/five-lane-fusion.md:\n  Line 36: The opt-in `SPECKIT_ADVISOR_RRF_FUSION` flag (default off) routes the same five lanes through Reciprocal Rank Fusion instead of the weighted blend, fusing each lane's ranked list with `ADVISOR_RRF_K = 8`. The conflict-rerank seam ships with the RRF core as its regression net: it repairs the one regression plain RRF introduces and corrects conflicting-recommendation cases. Phase 007 benchmarked the RRF spine and the seam on a 42-prompt set and verdicted GRADUATE the core paired with the seam, but the committed flag default stays off, so the weighted blend remains the live path until the flag is enabled.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md:\n  Line 275: Run `opencode providers list` to confirm credentials and `opencode models <provider>` for live choices. Default to `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro --variant high` (direct DeepSeek API); the MiniMax Token Plan default `minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` (omit `--agent`), the pay-per-token `minimax/MiniMax-M3` (Direct API), `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro --variant high` (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe — MiMo; high reasoning preset; omit `--agent`), `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro --variant high` (Xiaomi Direct API — MiMo; pay-per-token) and `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed --variant high` (low-latency MiMo tier, same prompt contract) remain available. The Kimi For Coding plan model `kimi-for-coding/k2p7` (\"Kimi K2.7 Code\"; 256k / 262,144-token context; subscription billing — dispatch cost 0; omit `--agent`; `--variant high` accepted but effect benchmark-unverified) is the coding-optimized large-context Kimi path. **Operational caveat (observed 2026-06-17):** on broad / large-repo scopes at `--variant high`, k2p7 over-explores (many sequential reads) and can exceed a 600s timeout WITHOUT emitting — opencode flushes only the final assistant message to stdout, so a killed run yields 0 bytes (looks like a hang, but it was working). Mitigate with a hard read-cap in the prompt (\"read ≤N files then emit\") + a 1200s+ timeout, or omit `--variant`. The Z.AI GLM Coding Plan model `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2` (\"GLM-5.2\"; flagship long-horizon coding; 1,000,000-token context / 131,072 output per Z.AI docs; subscription billing; omit `--agent`; `--variant`↔`reasoning_effort` mapping unverified — GLM has native high/max, smoke-test before relying on it; thinking on by default + preserved on the Coding Plan endpoint) is the Z.AI direct-provider GLM path, superseding the gateway-only `glm-5.1` removed in v1.3.15.0; confirm the live slug via `opencode models zai-coding-plan`. **Operational (benchmark 008, n=45):** thinking-on drives latency variance 6–161s (avg ~26s) — budget generous timeouts; expect ~1/45...\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/feature_catalog/08--python-compat/bench-runner.md:\n  Line 22: `scripts/skill_advisor_bench.py` drives the bench measurements. The design envelope is `cache-hit p95 <= 50 ms` and `uncached p95 <= 60 ms`, design ceilings rather than enforceable CI gates, since p95 timing varies with sandbox load. Current stable-workstation measurements are 6.989 ms (cache-hit p95) and 11.45 ms (uncached p95), well within the envelope. Daemon-side idle measurements are 0.031% CPU and 5.516 MB RSS. The CI wrapper at `mcp_server/stress_test/skill-advisor/python-bench-runner-stress.vitest.ts` verifies the subprocess surface and JSON envelope shape. Tightened p95 gating belongs in a stable benchmark environment, not the stress suite.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/bench/README.md:\n  Line 5:   - \"skill advisor benchmarks\"\n\n  Line 18: `skill_advisor/bench/` contains benchmark suites and baseline data for advisor latency, scorer calibration, watcher behavior, hook brief signal quality and code-graph integration paths. These files are measurement assets, not production runtime modules.\n\n  Line 22: - Tracks latency and calibration benchmarks for the advisor scorer.\n\n  Line 23: - Includes code-graph parsing and query latency benchmarks.\n\n  Line 32: +-- code-graph-parse-latency.bench.ts       # Code graph parse benchmark\n\n  Line 34: +-- code-graph-query-latency.bench.ts       # Query latency benchmark\n\n  Line 35: +-- hook-brief-signal-noise.bench.ts        # Hook brief signal benchmark\n\n  Line 36: +-- latency-bench.ts                        # Advisor latency benchmark\n\n  Line 37: +-- scorer-bench.ts                         # Scorer benchmark\n\n  Line 39: +-- scorer-calibration.bench.ts             # Scorer calibration benchmark\n\n  Line 40: +-- watcher-benchmark.ts                    # Watcher benchmark\n\n  Line 55: | `watcher-benchmark.ts` | Measures watcher behavior. |\n\n  Line 70: benchmark scenario\n\n  Line 85: | `watcher-benchmark.ts` | Benchmark | Watcher measurement. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/README.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Standalone package home for skill-advisor handlers, libraries, schemas, scripts, tests, benchmarks and database ownership.\"\n\n  Line 178: |   +-- watcher-benchmark.ts\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/README.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Python, shell and compiled graph utilities for skill-advisor routing, benchmarking, regression checks and skill-graph generation.\"\n\n  Line 18: `mcp_server/scripts/` holds command-line utilities and generated assets used by the skill-advisor package. The scripts support prompt routing checks, benchmark runs, regression validation, runtime invocation and skill-graph compilation.\n\n  Line 23: - Stores benchmark and regression scripts for advisor quality measurement.\n\n  Line 58: | `skill_advisor_bench.py` | Runs benchmark scenarios and reports timing or quality metrics. |\n\n  Line 74: | Ownership | Keep skill-advisor CLI, benchmark and graph generation utilities here. Put runtime TypeScript code in `../lib/`. |\n\n  Line 93: | `skill_advisor_bench.py` | Python CLI | Runs benchmark scenarios. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.14.0.md:\n  Line 14: 2. **MiniMax M2.7 removal** — All references to MiniMax-M2.7 (including `-highspeed` variants) have been removed. MiniMax-M3 is now the sole model for both `minimax-coding-plan` (Token Plan) and `minimax` (Direct API). The 120/003 benchmark (originally run on M2.7) TIDD-EC + dense contract is carried forward to M3.\n\n  Line 41: - The 120/003 benchmark TIDD-EC + dense contract is explicitly carried forward to M3 until re-benchmarked.\n\n  Line 47: - The MiniMax TIDD-EC + dense contract was benchmarked on M2.7; it carries forward to M3 pending re-benchmark.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/references/smart_routing.md:\n  Line 297: ## 11. MACHINE-READABLE ROUTER (replay / benchmark source)\n\n  Line 301: A drift guard (`.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/scripts/skill-benchmark/tests/sk-code-router-sync.vitest.ts`) keeps this block honest: it fails if any path here is missing on disk, if any routable `references/`/`assets/` doc stops being covered, or if an explicit full path named in the prose maps is absent here. Run it standalone with `npx vitest run skill-benchmark/tests/sk-code-router-sync.vitest.ts` from `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/scripts`.\n\n  Line 471: It does not load the other surface's resources, and it defers `assets/*` (checklists, recipes, templates) to on-demand rather than the first slice. Within OpenCode it slices once more by the **detected language** (§1 sub-detection): a TypeScript task loads `references/opencode/typescript/*` plus the language-agnostic `references/opencode/shared/*`, not the Python, shell, config, or JavaScript folders. Webflow has no language sub-slice — a frontend task legitimately spans CSS, HTML, and JavaScript together. A task that genuinely spans both surfaces (mixed `.opencode/` and Webflow markers) keeps both surface slices; an `UNKNOWN` surface falls back to the preamble plus the universal tier and the Motion overlay only. This is what stops a routine single-surface task from pulling the full cross-surface set. The deterministic router-replay enforces the same rule, so the benchmark measures it.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.6.0.md:\n  Line 4: **Status**: Documentation + registry addendum. Resolves the two items v1.3.5.0 left pending: MiMo-V2.5-Pro's capability metadata (research) and its best prompt framework (empirical benchmark). No default change — `opencode-go/deepseek-v4-pro` stays the skill default.\n\n  Line 10: v1.3.5.0 registered MiMo-V2.5-Pro with `context_length` and the best prompt framework marked **pending** (126/003 research + 126/004 benchmark). This release lands both results from real evidence:\n\n  Line 13: - **126/004 benchmark** (10/10 real `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` dispatches across 5 frameworks × 2 fixtures) named the empirical prompt-framework winner.\n\n  Line 46: - The framework benchmark was **re-run at `--variant high`** for both MiMo and MiniMax (a 2×2: model × default/high). **COSTAR holds as co-winner for MiMo at high reasoning** — at high the field *compresses* (even TIDD-EC's verbosity penalty largely vanishes: 151→66 words on the hard fixture; format-adherent frameworks went 2/5→4/5), so framework choice matters *less* at high reasoning, but COSTAR/RACE-lean stays the safe default. MiniMax → RACE on this 2-fixture rig — do NOT overwrite the 7-fixture 120/003 TIDD-EC recommendation (correctness saturates on 2 tractable fixtures). Framework (COSTAR) and reasoning (`--variant high`) are independent, composable levers.\n\n  Line 52: - Benchmark (default reasoning): `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/126-cli-opencode-mimo-pro-optimization/004-mimo-prompt-framework-benchmark/eval/synthesis.md`\n\n  Line 53: - Benchmark (`--variant high` 2×2 re-run): `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/126-cli-opencode-mimo-pro-optimization/004-mimo-prompt-framework-benchmark/eval/synthesis-high-reasoning.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.13.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release lands cli-opencode's deferred `cli_reference.md` edit and removes the extra leading divider from one asset doc. The reference doc gains a benchmark-confirmed MiniMax-M3 row plus the section dividers that phase 014 held back. No dispatch behavior changed.\n\n  Line 11: - **MiniMax-M3 row landed + dividers** -- `references/cli_reference.md` carried an uncommitted, benchmark-dated row documenting plain `minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` as a confirmed-live dispatchable id (20 clean benchmark dispatches, `--variant high` accepted). Phase 014 held this file back because of that content edit. It lands now together with the section dividers 014 had applied.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.5.0.md:\n  Line 12: MiMo is an **explicitly-selectable** model — it does not change any default. The best prompt framework is **not yet determined**: it will be benchmarked in 126/004, so no framework winner is claimed (no TIDD-EC / RCAF / any call). `context_length` and `--variant` behavior remain unknown pending 126/003.\n\n  Line 31: - **Prompt template**: Template 15 documents the dispatch shape only (framework neutral, pending benchmark).\n\n  Line 44: - Best prompt framework → pending 126/004 benchmark.\n\n  Line 48: - MiMo has not been benchmarked; do not assume MiniMax's TIDD-EC + dense pre-plan contract transfers.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.8.0.md:\n  Line 10: The MiniMax and MiMo benchmark-evidence citations in `assets/prompt_templates.md` pointed to spec sub-phase paths that were gutted when their run-data was relocated to the `sk-prompt-models/benchmarks/` hub. This release repoints all affected citations to the resolved hub paths so they remain accurate and navigable.\n\n  Line 18: | `assets/prompt_templates.md` | MiniMax (120/003) and MiMo (126/004) benchmark-evidence citation paths updated to `sk-prompt-models/benchmarks/` hub paths | Origin sub-phases now hold only a `BENCHMARK-RELOCATED.md` pointer; citations must resolve |\n\n  Line 26: - `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/131-registry-benchmark-consolidation/` — source packet for this change set\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/changelog/v1.3.4.0.md:\n  Line 4: **Status**: Documentation + config addendum. Integrates the 120/003 benchmark result (real MiniMax M2.7 runs) and corrects the MiniMax model slug from the placeholder written in 120/001.\n\n  Line 10: Packet `120/003-minimax-prompt-framework-benchmark` reused the 113 SWE-1.6 eval rig (7 fixtures, 5-dim rubric, claude grader) with the dispatch layer swapped to `opencode run --model minimax/MiniMax-M2.7`. It ran 7 iterations / 49 real MiniMax dispatches across 5 prompt frameworks + a pre-planning hill-climb.\n\n  Line 30: | `sk-prompt-models/assets/model-profiles.json` | Updated (sibling) | `minimax-2.7`: `context_length` 204800; notes/strengths reflect benchmark + correct slug |\n\n  Line 35: `.opencode/specs/skilled-agent-orchestration/120-cli-opencode-minimax-optimization/003-minimax-prompt-framework-benchmark/eval-loop/synthesis.md`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/agent_improvement/improvement_charter.md:\n  Line 52: - benchmark evidence is required for target profiles that declare fixtures\n\n  Line 54: - runtime mirrors are downstream packaging surfaces, not benchmark truth\n\n  Line 81: | Benchmark completion | `benchmark_completed` | candidateId, aggregateScore, fixtureResults |\n\n  Line 99: - **evidenceGate**: benchmark pass AND repeatability pass\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/agent_improvement/improvement_config_reference.md:\n  Line 9:   - \"model-benchmark mode config\"\n\n  Line 25: Documents each field in `improvement_config.json` so operators can tune scoring, benchmarking, stop rules, and file protection without guessing.\n\n  Line 68: | `maxWeakBenchmarkRunsPerProfile` | number | Stop after N weak benchmark results |\n\n  Line 75: The model-benchmark mode (run via `scripts/shared/loop-host.cjs --mode=model-benchmark`) is selected at the command line, not by a config field. Its operator-facing levers:\n\n  Line 79: | `--mode` | `loop-host.cjs` | `agent-improvement` (default) or `model-benchmark`. Unknown values warn and fall back to agent-improvement. |\n\n  Line 80: | `--scorer` | `run-benchmark.cjs` | `pattern` (default, byte-identical heading/pattern matcher) or `5dim` (routes outputs through `scripts/model-benchmark/scorer/score-model-variant.cjs`). |\n\n  Line 81: | `--grader` | `run-benchmark.cjs` | `noop` (default, deterministic), `mock`, or `llm`. Only consulted under `--scorer 5dim`. |\n\n  Line 92: - `../../references/model_benchmark/evaluator_contract.md`: scoring rubric details\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/agent_improvement/target-profiles/README.md:\n  Line 24: - Static benchmark profiles for the model-benchmark lane live elsewhere, under `../../model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/`.\n\n  Line 35: | Scope | Agent-improvement profiles only. Model-benchmark profiles belong to `../../model-benchmark/benchmark-profiles/`. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/agent_improvement/README.md:\n  Line 36: | `improvement_config_reference.md` | Field-level reference for `improvement_config.json`: documents top-level, scoring, and stop-rule fields, plus the command-line model-benchmark levers (`--mode`, `--scorer`, `--grader`) and their env switches. |\n\n  Line 69: - [`model-benchmark README`](../../scripts/model-benchmark/README.md)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/agent_improvement/improvement_strategy.md:\n  Line 16: Mutable strategy template for a deep-improvement run. Use it to capture the operator-owned goal and hypothesis while reserving the machine-owned sections for reducer updates after scoring and benchmarking.\n\n  Line 28: Copy this file into the runtime area, fill the operator-owned fields before the run, and let the reducer update the machine-owned status sections after each score or benchmark cycle.\n\n  Line 50: - runtime mirrors excluded from benchmark truth\n\n  Line 77: [Reducer updates after scoring and benchmarking]\n\n  Line 93: [Reducer updates after scoring and benchmarking]\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:\n  Line 90: The Resource Loading Levels table above is the human-readable view; the fenced block below is the machine-parseable router that drives deterministic routing and the skill-benchmark D5 connectivity gate. `INTENT_SIGNALS` scores the lowercased task by keyword, `RESOURCE_MAP` maps each intent to the in-skill references and assets it loads, and `DEFAULT_RESOURCE` is loaded on every design task. Routing semantics match the table one-for-one: the same references load for the same intents. The shared register (`../shared/register.md`) is loaded on every task via `DEFAULT_RESOURCE`. It lives in the parent skill's `shared/` dir, a sanctioned cross-packet location the D5 gate recognizes.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/references/webflow/debugging/debugging_workflows.md:\n  Line 984: **Automated performance measurement enables objective benchmarking and regression detection:**\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/skill_benchmark/fixtures/deep-loop-workflows/routing-precision.md:\n  Line 5: deep-skill-routing endpoint. NOTE: the skill-benchmark *harness* itself scores\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/skill_benchmark/fixtures/README.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"fixtures: legacy Mode A skill-benchmark corpus\"\n\n  Line 3: description: \"Per-skill public/private fixture pairs for the legacy Mode A (--fixtures-dir) skill-benchmark corpus; superseded by the in-skill manual_testing_playbook but still supported.\"\n\n  Line 5:   - \"skill-benchmark fixtures\"\n\n  Line 12: # fixtures: legacy Mode A skill-benchmark corpus\n\n  Line 18: `fixtures/` holds the legacy Mode A skill-benchmark corpus, organized as per-skill directories (`<skill-id>/`) each containing one or more `<scenario>.public.json` / `<scenario>.private.json` pairs. The skill-benchmark loop consumes this corpus via `--fixtures-dir`. The PUBLIC half of a pair is the only material that crosses the dispatch boundary to the agent under test; the PRIVATE half is scorer-only gold and never reaches the model. This corpus is superseded by the skill's own `manual_testing_playbook` (the default corpus) but remains supported for explicit `--fixtures-dir` runs.\n\n  Line 56: | Consumers | Read by the skill-benchmark loop only when invoked with `--fixtures-dir` (Mode A). The default corpus is the in-skill `manual_testing_playbook`. |\n\n  Line 58: | Write policy | Static gold inputs. Edits are authored deliberately; the benchmark loop reads but does not mutate them. |\n\n  Line 65: - [`model-benchmark README`](../../../scripts/model-benchmark/README.md)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/skill_benchmark/README.md:\n  Line 2: title: \"skill-benchmark assets: Lane C reference data\"\n\n  Line 5:   - \"skill benchmark profile\"\n\n\n(Results truncated. Consider using a more specific path or pattern.)","metadata":{"matches":100,"truncated":true},"title":"FIX-5|host hard identity|semantic wrong-mode|route-proof mismatch|latency ga