l`\n\n  Line 473: **Note:** The `.codex/agents/*.toml` files define agent personas for the interactive multi-agent TUI feature (requires `multi_agent` feature flag). They are NOT loaded by the `-p` profile flag. To use agent-specific settings in `codex exec`, define corresponding `[profiles.<name>]` sections in config.toml.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/opencode/checklists/command_authoring.md:\n  Line 3: description: Checklist for authoring slash commands with execution-path YAML, runtime mirrors, and verification gates.\n\n  Line 8:   - \"command runtime mirrors\"\n\n  Line 16: Checklist for authoring or modifying `/<command>` slash commands with consistent command markdown, execution-path YAML, runtime mirrors, and verification gates.\n\n  Line 22: This checklist keeps `/<command>` workflows consistent across command markdown, execution-path YAML, and runtime mirrors. It is for commands that users invoke directly, especially commands that dispatch agents, write spec folders, or route through create/spec-kit workflows.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code/assets/opencode/checklists/agent_authoring.md:\n  Line 3: description: Checklist for authoring OpenCode agents with clear authority boundaries, permissions, dispatch contracts, and runtime mirrors.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-code-review/changelog/v1.5.0.0.md:\n  Line 13: Six files were `references/` but are really checklist artifacts a reviewer applies, not doctrine a reviewer reads: `code_quality_checklist.md`, `security_checklist.md`, `solid_checklist.md`, `test_quality_checklist.md`, `fix-completeness-checklist.md`, and `removal_plan.md`. They moved to a new `assets/` folder. The four genuine references stayed in `references/`: `review_core.md` (doctrine), `review_ux_single_pass.md` (single-pass UX behavior), `quick_reference.md` (index), and `pr_state_dedup.md` (the M-1 dedup spec). Every by-path reference was updated in lockstep — the §2 routing tables and `RESOURCE_MAP`, the README table, `graph-metadata.json`, the bidirectional sibling cross-links, nineteen manual-testing per-feature files, and the two cross-skill `sk-code/references/opencode/{python,shell}/quality_standards.md` pointers. The `.claude` and `.codex` runtime mirrors were re-synced. The rule canary keys on `pr_state_dedup.md` (which stayed), so it remains green.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-code-graph/references/runtime/naming_conventions.md:\n  Line 50: | MCP server name | `mk-code-index` | `opencode.json` `mcp.mk_code_index.*` and 5 runtime mirrors | Stable tool contract per ADR-002. Renaming would break every config that registers the server. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-doc/changelog/v1.5.0.0.md:\n  Line 3: First major iteration of `sk-doc` after the v1.3.0.0 series. Packet 102 ships five sequential phases that restructure the skill surface: reference relocation, a dedicated skill README asset, an agent identity rename across three runtime mirrors, manual playbook coverage for the renamed agent, and a single transactional remediation pass that closes every P1 and P2 finding from the phase-parent deep-review. All five phases land as additive child packets in `skilled-agent-orchestration/102-sk-doc-skill-readme-and-structure`. The `/create:*` command family stays surface-stable.\n\n  Line 25: The dedicated documentation executor agent renames from `@create` to `@markdown` across all three runtime mirrors: `.opencode/agents/markdown.md`, `.claude/agents/markdown.md`, and `.codex/agents/markdown.toml`. The Codex registry block updates from `[agents.create]` to `[agents.markdown]` with `config_file = \"agents/markdown.toml\"`. Orchestrator and code-agent references route documentation and component authoring through `@markdown`. The `/create:*` command family (`/create:agent`, `/create:sk-skill`, `/create:feature-catalog`, `/create:testing-playbook`, `/create:folder_readme`, `/create:changelog`) keeps every invocation unchanged because this is an agent identity rename, not a command-family rename.\n\n  Line 74: | Old-identity grep across runtime mirrors and commands after Phase 003      | PASS, zero `@create` / `create.md` / `create.toml`  |\n\n  Line 75: | New-file presence test for the three runtime mirrors after Phase 003       | PASS, all three `markdown.*` files exist            |\n\n  Line 99: Downstream agents and orchestrators that previously typed `@create` as the documentation executor MUST switch to `@markdown`. The rename applies to all three runtime mirrors. Specifically:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-context/SKILL.md:\n  Line 279: The native `@deep-context` seat is dispatched **by name** (`agent: deep-context` in the loop YAML), resolved by each host runtime from its OWN `agents/` directory. It therefore lives as one canonical source plus two runtime mirrors that must stay in sync:\n\n  Line 302: 8. **Keep the native agent's runtime mirrors in sync** — when editing `.opencode/agents/deep-context.md` (canonical), update `.claude/agents/deep-context.md` and `.opencode/agents/deep-context.toml` in the same change. The loop dispatches the native seat by name from each runtime's own `agents/` dir, so a missing mirror means native seats silently fail to dispatch in that runtime. See **Runtime Mirrors** in §3.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 167: Verify runtime mirrors expose `deep-ai-council` and active mirror paths do not retain `ai-council` as the primary identity.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/manual_testing_playbook/02--council-deliberation-and-seat-diversity/three-seat-diverse-deliberation.md:\n  Line 67: Check the reference first, then the agent strategy section, then runtime mirrors if parity is suspect.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-runtime/SKILL.md:\n  Line 255: This runtime is MCP-free and owns no agents, but every deep loop that consumes it ships a **native agent** that the loop dispatches **by name** (`agent: <name>` in the loop YAML), which each host runtime resolves from its OWN `agents/` dir. Each such agent — `deep-context`, `deep-research`, `deep-review`, `deep-improvement`, `ai-council` — is one canonical source plus two runtime mirrors carrying the same body:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/manual_testing_playbook/01--runtime-routing-and-rename/runtime-agent-renamed-to-deep-ai-council.md:\n  Line 15: This scenario validates that runtime mirrors expose `deep-ai-council` as the active identity.\n\n  Line 25: - Objective: Verify active runtime mirrors use `deep-ai-council`.\n\n  Line 29: - Expected signals: New name appears in all four runtime mirrors; old name is absent as an active agent name.\n\n  Line 31: - Pass/fail: PASS if all runtime mirrors expose `deep-ai-council`; FAIL if an active mirror still names `multi-ai-council`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/references/structure/output_schema.md:\n  Line 130: 2. Update `@deep-ai-council` agent body §8 in all four runtime mirrors.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/references/structure/folder_layout.md:\n  Line 22: **Persistence is mandatory for every council run.** The target packet path is resolved by the agent at §1 Step 0 RESOLVE in `deep-ai-council.md` across all 4 runtime mirrors. When invocation cannot resolve a packet path, the agent HALT-and-ASKs the user for one and does NOT dispatch council seats, so the layout below applies to every completed deliberation.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 82: No migration is required. Phase 003's council graph is a derived projection — existing `ai-council/` artifacts produced before this release remain authoritative and replayable. Callers already using `@deep-ai-council` need no changes; the agent body and runtime mirrors are stable. The playbook count grew from 18 to 32 scenarios; if external tooling counts playbook entries, update those counters.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:\n  Line 21: The runtime agent now ships as `@deep-ai-council` across all three runtime mirrors (OpenCode, Claude, Codex). The agent body documents the 9-step workflow from RESOLVE through DELIVER, the dispatch depth rules (Depth 0 parallel via `Task`, Depth 1 sequential via `sequential_thinking` MCP), and the persistence protocol that calls writer functions in a fixed order so every artifact lands with an audit event.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/changelog/v1.2.0.0.md:\n  Line 5: Renamed the skill `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/` → `.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/` and the agent `.opencode/agents/deep-ai-council.{md,toml}` → `.opencode/agents/ai-council.{md,toml}` across all three runtime mirrors. Family moved from `deep-loop` to `sk-util` per the parent spec.md §2 rationale: the Council is a planning sentinel skill (closer to sk-prompt's role) rather than an autonomous-loop executor like deep-research/deep-review which iterate to convergence. Behavior, trigger phrases, MCP wiring, council graph projection, and deliberation logic are all unchanged — this is a pure identity refactor.\n\n  Line 31: | Other runtime mirrors | 3 orchestrate.md/.toml agent files (delegation targets) + `.codex/config.toml` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/agent_improvement/improvement_charter.md:\n  Line 54: - runtime mirrors are downstream packaging surfaces, not benchmark truth\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/assets/agent_improvement/improvement_strategy.md:\n  Line 50: - runtime mirrors excluded from benchmark truth\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/README.md:\n  Line 36: Editing an agent prompt is normally guesswork. You reword a rule, the prompt reads better, you ship it and you never learn whether the agent got stronger or only different. Integration drift across runtime mirrors goes unnoticed because nothing checks every surface the agent touches. Promotion risk is hard to audit because no paper trail links score evidence to the mutation decision. Rollback is neither systematic nor comparable to the pre-promotion state.\n\n  Line 81: An agent is more than its `.md` file. `scan-integration.cjs` inventories the canonical agent definition, three runtime mirrors (`.opencode/agents/`, `.claude/agents/`, `.opencode/agents/`), command dispatch files, YAML workflow assets, skill references and the skill-advisor routing path. The scanner extracts emphasized strings from the canonical agent and marks a mirror aligned when enough of them appear. A drifted mirror shows up before it causes a runtime surprise, and the score reflects the whole integration surface, not the prompt in isolation. Mirror parity is also enforced repo-wide outside a scoring run: `scripts/check-agent-mirror-sync.cjs` gates commits (through `.opencode/hooks/pre-commit`) and pull requests into `main` (through `.github/workflows/agent-mirror-sync.yml`), so drifted runtime copies are caught before they merge. The commit hook fails open when Node or the checker is unavailable so it never blocks an unrelated commit; the CI gate on `main` is the fail-closed backstop.\n\n  Line 120: Run `deep-improvement` when you want to prove an agent edit earned its place before you commit it. Run it when integration drift across runtime mirrors worries you and you need a scanner to find every surface. Run Lane B when a model or prompt framework needs benchmark comparison against repeatable fixtures. Run Lane C when a skill's routing accuracy or discoverability needs measurement. Run Lane D when a multi-packaging AI system (CLI runtime, claude.ai Project, native skill) needs guarded benchmark-and-refine against an independent different-family grader.\n\n  Line 161: A: It finds every file that references an agent: the canonical definition, three runtime mirrors, command dispatch files, YAML workflow references, skill SKILL.md mentions and the skill-advisor routing entry. It extracts emphasized strings from the canonical agent and marks a mirror aligned when enough of them appear.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-review/SKILL.md:\n  Line 19: - OpenCode runtime: `.opencode/agents/*.toml` when running directly in OpenCode; external OpenCode dispatch uses `cli-opencode`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/SKILL.md:\n  Line 20: - OpenCode runtime: `.opencode/agents/*.toml`\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:\n  Line 35: Scenario IDs: DAC-001..DAC-002. How council requests reach the skill and how the runtime mirrors identify it.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-ai-council/feature_catalog/01--runtime-routing-and-rename/runtime-agent-renamed-to-deep-ai-council.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Verify active runtime mirrors use deep-ai-council.\"\n\n  Line 19: Verify active runtime mirrors use deep-ai-council.\n\n  Line 31: Current behavior is grounded in `.opencode/agents/ai-council.md`, which the scenario identifies as the OpenCode runtime mirror. Identity note: the agent files are `ai-council.*` (the `@ai-council` identity) because v1.2.0.0 dropped the `deep-` prefix from the agent, while the skill kept the `deep-ai-council` name. The runtime mirrors route council prompts to the `deep-ai-council` skill under the `@ai-council` agent identity. Validation is anchored by `manual_testing_playbook/01--runtime-routing-and-rename/runtime-agent-renamed-to-deep-ai-council.md`, covering the manual scenario contract.\n\n  Line 33: The user-visible contract is concrete: Verify active runtime mirrors use deep-ai-council. The catalog entry mirrors that contract so reviewers can move from feature inventory to the exact playbook scenario and source files without guessing.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/feature_catalog.md:\n  Line 162: These entries describe how deep-improvement discovers the full agent surface across the repo, evaluates runtime mirrors, and wires command-driven orchestration through the deep-improvement command and YAML workflows.\n\n  Line 172: `scan-integration.cjs` scans the canonical agent file, three runtime mirrors, improve command markdown, YAML workflow assets, skill references, global docs, and a skill-advisor path constant. That path now points at `.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/scripts/skill_advisor.py`, so the consolidated skill-advisor surface is included in the integration map.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/01--evaluation-loop/rollback.md:\n  Line 29: The rollback helper is deliberately narrow. It does not emit journal rows, re-run the scorer, or reconcile runtime mirrors by itself. Those follow-on checks live in the rollback runbook and surrounding orchestration, which keeps file restoration separate from audit logging and packaging review.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/01--evaluation-loop/candidate-generation.md:\n  Line 29: The YAML workflows own when candidate generation happens. Autonomous mode runs the proposal step whenever the loop continues, while confirm mode adds an approval gate before dispatching the candidate writer. The packet-local boundary is strict in the shipped agent: canonical targets and runtime mirrors are explicit never-edit surfaces.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/changelog/v1.2.2.0.md:\n  Line 22: | `.codex/agents/*.toml` | Modified | Runtime-specific deep-research and deep-review packet guidance synchronized |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-review/manual_testing_playbook/07--command-flow-stress-tests/write-boundary-reducer-owned-files.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"Validate that @deep-review refuses instructions to edit review targets, runtime mirrors, config, registry, dashboard, or report files.\"\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-review/manual_testing_playbook/07--command-flow-stress-tests/setup-yaml-handoff.md:\n  Line 38: 1. Create `/tmp/cp-052-sandbox/` with command, skill, system helpers, and runtime mirrors.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/02--integration-scanning/surface-discovery.md:\n  Line 27: `scan-integration.cjs` inventories the canonical `.opencode/agents/{name}.md` file, runtime mirrors, improve-command markdown, YAML workflow assets, skill references, global docs, and one skill-advisor lookup. Command markdown is scanned for `@{agent}` dispatch, while YAML is scanned for either `@{agent}` or bare agent-name references.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/references/agent_improvement/mirror_drift_policy.md:\n  Line 30: - runtime mirrors may now be stale\n\n  Line 60: Use `scan-integration.cjs` as the primary tool for detecting mirror drift. It replaces manual file-by-file comparison with automated signal-matching across all 3 runtime mirrors:\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/feature_catalog/02--integration-scanning/runtime-mirrors.md:\n  Line 5:   - \"runtime mirrors\"\n\n  Line 29: `scan-integration.cjs` checks the canonical file plus repo-managed runtime mirrors via hardcoded templates: `.opencode/agents/{name}.md` (canonical), `.claude/agents/{name}.md`, and `.opencode/agents/{name}.toml`.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/SKILL.md:\n  Line 524: - Treat runtime mirrors as experiment truth in the same phase as canonical evaluation\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/references/shared/promotion_rules.md:\n  Line 94: - agent-definition targets are present and content-aligned across all four runtime mirrors; OpenCode TOML is checked by extracted body tokens, not by byte-equivalence of the TOML wrapper\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/changelog/v1.9.0.0.md:\n  Line 54: - **The `@deep-improvement` awareness note went from \"Mode awareness\" to \"Lane awareness\"** across all 4 runtime mirrors, byte-identical (mirror-drift 0). The note makes clear there is one agent and Lane B dispatches models through `dispatch-model.cjs`, never a second Claude agent.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/changelog/v1.0.0.0.md:\n  Line 31: The `scan-integration.cjs` script discovers every surface an agent touches across the repo: main definition, 3 runtime mirrors (Claude, Codex, .agents), command dispatch references, YAML workflow references, skill mentions, global doc references, and skill advisor routing entries. Mirror sync is detected by signal-string matching against the main body.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/scripts/agent-improvement/README.md:\n  Line 81: | `scan-integration.cjs` | Scans the three runtime mirrors, commands, YAML workflows, skills, global docs, and the skill advisor for an agent name. CLI: `--agent=<name>` with optional `--repo-root` and `--output`. Emits `status: 'complete'` with `surfaces` and `summary`. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 612: Confirm `@deep-improvement` writes only packet-local candidates and never mutates canonical targets or runtime mirrors.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-review/changelog/v1.3.1.0.md:\n  Line 25: When an operator re-entered a review session, the interactive workflow asked which lifecycle mode to use: `resume` (continue where you left off), `restart` (archive the old run and start a new generation), `fork` (start a sibling run history), or `completed-continue` (reopen a finished run after snapshotting its synthesis). The first two were real. The last two were documented in several places but had no actual workflow wiring - selecting them did nothing different, and the state log silently kept the old session id. Anyone who believed they had branched a review was quietly overwriting their previous work. `fork` and `completed-continue` are now explicitly marked as deferred (reserved for a future release) everywhere the skill mentions them: `SKILL.md`, `README.md`, both loop-protocol references, both command workflows, the main agent definition, and the runtime mirrors across all three CLI runtimes. The interactive gate now offers three choices - `resume`, `restart`, or `cancel`. Both paths append a typed event to the state log that carries the full run history field set (session id, parent session id, run history mode, continued-from-run, generation, archive path, timestamp). A parity test locks the new option list so the retraction cannot silently drift back.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-review/changelog/v1.1.0.0.md:\n  Line 1: This release hardens `deep-review` into a fully explicit review-packet expected behavior. The skill now has main `deep-review-*` naming across all surfaces, an unambiguous lifecycle and reducer model, synchronized runtime mirrors, and focused Vitest guards that keep the expected behavior from drifting. The goal is to make the workflow easier to follow and easier to trust.\n\n  Line 7: - Canonical review artifacts are now frozen across the skill, references, workflow assets, and runtime mirrors: `deep-review-config.json`, `deep-review-state.jsonl`, `deep-review-findings-registry.json`, `.deep-review-pause`, and `deep-review-dashboard.md`.\n\n  Line 16: - OpenCode, Claude, and Codex runtime mirrors now all point at the same review packet model.\n\n  Line 62: No migration is required for current `deep-review` consumers. The main change is that review packets now use one canonical naming, lifecycle, reducer, and readiness model across docs, workflows, runtime mirrors, and tests.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-research/changelog/v1.4.0.0.md:\n  Line 7: - Canonical `deep-research-*` packet artifacts are now frozen across the skill docs, references, runtime mirrors, and workflow assets.\n\n  Line 33: - Added `deep-research-expected behavior-parity.vitest.ts` to keep the docs, command assets, capability matrix, and runtime mirrors synchronized.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/deep-loop-workflows/deep-improvement/manual_testing_playbook/08--agent-discipline-stress-tests/proposal-only-boundary.md:\n  Line 44: - Pass/fail: PASS if Call B candidate path is packet-local, candidate evidence is proposal-only, and canonical/mirror diffs are empty. FAIL if Call B edits canonical or runtime mirrors before explicit promotion.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.4.1.0.md:\n  Line 309: The council writes its own artifact tree. Permission across the three runtime mirrors: `write: allow / edit: allow`; `bash: deny / patch: deny`. Path-scope to `ai-council/**` is enforced by the writer library, `scripts/ai-council/lib/persist-artifacts.js` throws `OUT_OF_SCOPE_WRITE` for any out-of-bounds target. The audit-trail schema is additive v1.1 → v1.2 with new `artifact_written` and `rollback` event types; v1 readers continue to parse v1.2 files unchanged. Round-NNN folder is the rollback unit; on seat error or convergence failure, the round artifacts move to `failed/round-NNN-<timestamp>/` and the audit trail records `superseded_by: \"rollback\"` markers. Three ADRs (write-permission model, audit-trail schema, rollback semantics) document the decisions. 7 new vitest cases cover permission-scope, runtime-parity, audit-trail, and rollback.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/references/workflows/rename_pattern.md:\n  Line 24: Define the reusable workflow and checklist for mechanical rename refactors across skills, agents, docs, memory, indexes, and runtime mirrors.\n\n  Line 44: | **Live runtime mirrors** | `.claude/agents/`, `.opencode/agents/` + corresponding READMEs | `git mv` + literal substitution |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.2.1.0.md:\n  Line 54: Packet 040 brought both autonomous workflows onto one stronger contract model. This matters to System Spec Kit because the command assets, runtime mirrors, and contract tests now live on explicit executable rules instead of documentation-only alignment.\n\n  Line 58: The deep-research workflow still relied on scattered wording for run history, lifecycle branches, reducer ownership, packet artifacts, and runtime parity. That made the expected behavior easier to drift and harder to audit. Deep-research now has main run history fields, lifecycle modes, reducer-owned outputs, runtime capability surfaces, and executable helpers. The workflow YAML, skill docs, runtime mirrors, and packet-closeout rules all point at the same packet model.\n\n  Line 68: Without targeted tests, deep-research and deep-review could drift back out of sync across docs, command assets, and runtime mirrors while still looking plausible on manual inspection. Focused Vitest suites in the System Spec Kit scripts workspace now guard both expected behaviors directly: deep-research parity plus reducer idempotency, and deep-review parity plus reducer/readiness schemas. That makes future drift visible quickly and keeps the expected behaviors executable.\n\n  Line 73: Autonomous workflow instructions can silently diverge across OpenCode, Claude, Codex, and compatibility wrappers when each runtime surface is patched separately. Packet 040 synchronized all runtime mirrors for both deep-research and deep-review in one pass, so lifecycle vocabulary, reducer-owned surfaces, and packet file expectations now move together instead of fragmenting by runtime.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/changelog/v3.0.0.3.md:\n  Line 44: | `.opencode/agents/*.md` + `.claude/agents/*.md` + `.codex/agents/*.toml` | Modified | Runtime parity updates |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/scripts/tests/fixtures/multi-ai-council/council-output-full.md:\n  Line 125: Implement `persist-artifacts.cjs` as a parse-and-write helper under `system-spec-kit/scripts/ai-council/`. Add the markdown schema reference and fixture-driven tests. Then update the agent body and runtime mirrors with a caller-owned persistence protocol.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/feature_catalog/04--maintenance/doctor-router-and-manifest-dispatch.md:\n  Line 63: ### Cross-runtime mirrors\n","metadata":{"matches":82,"truncated":false},"title":"\\.opencode/agents/\\*\\.toml|agents/\\*\\.toml|\\.toml mirror|toml mirror|OpenCode runtime: `.opencode/agents/\\*\\.toml`|runtime mirrors","time":{"start":1782919103859,"end":1782919104044}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0c0a1c33a516776a016a452fbf2ed88198b15810e9c6c3c3a2"}},"id":"prt_f1e42855b0016fcOc3xyjrzOO5","sessionID":"ses_0e1c04adcffe04QJWsDQQqIgY4","messageID":"msg_f1e4214830010Zd3w5awbnkB71"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1782919104047,"sessionID":"ses_0e1c04adcffe04QJWsDQQqIgY4","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_JYBJAJphQXLu3vqzB6OsGh8y","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"Command-only|command-only|direct dispatch|direct invocation|opencode run --agent ai-council|--agent ai-council","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 36 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/sk-prompt/SKILL.md:\n  Line 27: - Supporting indirect invocation from `@prompt-improver` agent dispatches (the deep-path escalation target for CLI fast-path prompt cards)\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_templates.md:\n  Line 388:   --agent ai-council \\\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 417: Verify `--agent ai-council` produces at least 3 distinct solution strategies scored across at least 3 dimensions with an explicit recommendation, AND respects the planning-only constraint (no file modifications).\n\n  Line 421: Prompt summary: As an external-AI conductor planning a CommonJS-to-ESM migration of a single hypothetical module, dispatch --agent ai-council to compare three strategies (big-bang rewrite, incremental wrapper, dual-build). Verify the response presents three distinct strategies, scores each across risk/effort/timeline/reversibility, recommends one with rationale and does NOT modify any files in the repo.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/manual_testing_playbook/04--agent-routing/multi-ai-council-multi-strategy.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"This scenario validates the ai-council planning-only agent for `CO-017`. It focuses on confirming `--agent ai-council` produces multiple distinct strategies scored across a rubric and respects the planning-only constraint (no file modifications).\"\n\n  Line 15: This scenario validates the Ultra-think multi-strategy planning agent for `CO-017`. It focuses on confirming `--agent ai-council` generates at least 3 distinct solution strategies, scores each across a multi-dimension rubric, recommends one with rationale, AND respects the planning-only constraint documented in `references/agent_delegation.md` §7 (no file modifications).\n\n  Line 27: - Objective: Confirm `--agent ai-council` produces at least 3 distinct strategies scored on at least 3 dimensions with an explicit recommendation, AND no file modifications occur.\n\n  Line 28: - Real user request: `Use opencode run with --agent ai-council to compare 3 strategies for migrating a small JS module from CommonJS to ESM. Confirm the response has 3 strategies, each scored on at least 3 dimensions, an explicit recommendation, AND no files were modified.`\n\n  Line 29: - RCAF Prompt: `As an external-AI conductor planning a CommonJS-to-ESM migration of a single hypothetical module, dispatch --agent ai-council to compare three strategies (big-bang rewrite, incremental wrapper, dual-build). Verify the response presents three distinct strategies, scores each across risk/effort/timeline/reversibility, recommends one with rationale, and does NOT modify any files in the repo. Return a concise pass/fail verdict naming the recommended strategy and the dimension count per strategy.`\n\n  Line 30: - Expected execution process: External-AI orchestrator snapshots a few sentinel file mtimes, dispatches with `--agent ai-council`, validates the response presents three distinct strategies with scoring across at least three dimensions and an explicit recommendation and confirms the sentinel mtimes are unchanged.\n\n  Line 43: 3. Dispatch with `--agent ai-council` and the multi-strategy planning prompt.\n\n  Line 51: | CO-017 | Ultra-think multi-strategy planning | Confirm `--agent ai-council` produces 3+ distinct strategies scored across 3+ dimensions with no file writes | `As an external-AI conductor planning a CommonJS-to-ESM migration of a single hypothetical module, dispatch --agent ai-council to compare three strategies (big-bang rewrite, incremental wrapper, dual-build). Verify the response presents three distinct strategies, scores each across risk/effort/timeline/reversibility, recommends one with rationale, and does NOT modify any files in the repo. Return a concise pass/fail verdict naming the recommended strategy and the dimension count per strategy.` | 1. `bash: stat -f '%m %N' .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md > /tmp/co-017-mtimes-before.txt && cat /tmp/co-017-mtimes-before.txt` -> 2. `bash: opencode run --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro --agent ai-council --variant high --format json --dir \"$(pwd)\" \"Compare three strategies for migrating a single CommonJS Node module to ESM: (1) big-bang rewrite, (2) incremental wrapper, (3) dual-build. Score each across risk, effort, timeline, and reversibility. Recommend one with rationale. PLANNING-ONLY — do not modify any files.\" > /tmp/co-017-events.jsonl 2>&1` -> 3. `bash: echo \"Exit: $?\"` -> 4. `bash: stat -f '%m %N' .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/SKILL.md .opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md > /tmp/co-017-mtimes-after.txt && diff /tmp/co-017-mtimes-before.txt /tmp/co-017-mtimes-after.txt && echo SENTINEL_MTIMES_OK` -> 5. `bash: jq -r 'select(.type == \"tool.call\") \\| .payload.name' /tmp/co-017-events.jsonl \\| grep -ciE '(Edit\\|Write)'` -> 6. `bash: jq -r 'select(.type == \"message.delta\" or .type == \"session.completed\") \\| .payload' /tmp/co-017-events.jsonl \\| grep -ciE '(big-bang\\|incremental wrapper\\|dual-build)'` -> 7. `bash: jq -r 'select(.type == \"message.delta\" or .type == \"session.completed\") \\| .payload' /tmp/co-017-events.jsonl \\| grep...\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-opencode/references/agent_delegation.md:\n  Line 197: **Command-only (as of `mode: subagent`).** Direct `opencode run --agent ai-council` is no longer reachable — `ai-council.md` is `mode: subagent`, not directly selectable as a top-level session agent. Dispatch via `/deep:ai-council` for a full session, or via `opencode run --agent general \"...\"` and let `general`/`orchestrate`'s own routing Task-dispatch to `@ai-council` for a single planning pass.\n\n  Line 227: | Iterative research loop | `deep-research` | **Command-only.** Dispatch via `/deep:research` (or `/deep:research:auto`). Direct `opencode run --agent deep-research` is forbidden; the parent command owns iteration state, JSONL, and convergence. |\n\n  Line 228: | Iterative code review loop | `deep-review` | **Command-only.** Dispatch via `/deep:review` (or `/deep:review:auto`). Direct `opencode run --agent deep-review` is forbidden; the parent command owns iteration state and severity-weighted convergence. |\n\n  Line 229: | Multi-strategy planning | `ai-council` | **Command-only.** Dispatch via `/deep:ai-council` for a full session, or `opencode run --agent general --variant high --format json --dir /repo \"Plan the authentication redesign — compare three strategies.\"` and let orchestrate's routing Task-dispatch `@ai-council`. Direct `opencode run --agent ai-council` is forbidden as of `mode: subagent`. |\n\n  Line 230: | Agent improvement | `deep-agent-improvement` | **Command-only.** Dispatch via `/deep:agent-improvement`. Direct `opencode run --agent deep-agent-improvement` is forbidden; the parent command owns evaluation, candidates, and promotion. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-claude-code/assets/prompt_templates.md:\n  Line 402:   --agent ai-council --model claude-opus-4-6 --permission-mode plan --output-format text 2>&1\n\n  Line 409:   --agent ai-council --model claude-opus-4-6 --permission-mode plan --output-format text 2>&1\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-claude-code/SKILL.md:\n  Line 279: | Multi-strategy planning | `ai-council` | `claude -p \"Plan the authentication redesign\" --agent ai-council --permission-mode plan --output-format text 2>&1` |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-claude-code/manual_testing_playbook/manual_testing_playbook.md:\n  Line 403: Verify `--agent ai-council --model claude-opus-4-6 --permission-mode plan` produces multiple distinct strategies scored across at least 3 dimensions for a complex planning task.\n\n  Line 407: Prompt: As an external-AI conductor planning a complex migration (for example MongoDB to PostgreSQL) and wanting multiple strategies evaluated by rubric, dispatch claude -p --agent ai-council --model claude-opus-4-6 --permission-mode plan and capture the structured plan. Verify the response generates at least 3 distinct strategies (for example big-bang, gradual, dual-write), scores each across risk/effort/timeline/rollback, and recommends one with rationale. Return a concise user-facing pass/fail verdict with the main reason.\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-claude-code/manual_testing_playbook/04--agent-routing/multi-ai-council-multi-strategy-planning.md:\n  Line 3: description: \"This scenario validates Ultra-think multi-strategy planning for `CC-014`. It focuses on confirming `--agent ai-council --model claude-opus-4-6 --permission-mode plan` produces multiple distinct scored strategies.\"\n\n  Line 15: This scenario validates Ultra-think multi-strategy planning for `CC-014`. It focuses on confirming `--agent ai-council --model claude-opus-4-6 --permission-mode plan` produces multiple distinct scored strategies.\n\n  Line 27: - Objective: Confirm `--agent ai-council --model claude